title: AFC's Blackened Tilapia with Grilled Vegetables
summary: You can never have too many main course recipes, so give AFC's Blackened Tilapia with Grilled Vegetables a try. For $5.02 per serving, this recipe covers 45% of your daily requirements of vitamins and minerals. One portion of this dish contains roughly 45g of protein, 24g of fat, and a total of 744 calories. This recipe serves 4. This recipe is liked by 13 foodies and cooks. It is perfect for The Fourth Of July. A mixture of brown rice, mrs. dash table blend & onion herb seasoning, bell peppers, and a handful of other ingredients are all it takes to make this recipe so flavorful. To use up the seasoning blend you could follow this main course with the Pumpkin Pie Spice Cream Scones as a dessert. From preparation to the plate, this recipe takes approximately 45 minutes. It is a good option if you're following a gluten free, dairy free, and pescatarian diet. With a spoonacular score of 97%, this dish is spectacular. Similar recipes are Grilled Blackened Tilapia, Grilled Lemon Tilapian and Summer Vegetables in a Foil Packet, and Blackened Tilapia.

winePairing.pairingText: Pinot Grigio, Gruener Veltliner, and Pinot Noir are my top picks for Tilapia. Fish is as diverse as wine, so it's hard to pick wines that go with every fish. A crisp white wine, such as a pinot grigio or Grüner Veltliner, will suit any delicately flavored white fish. Meaty, strongly flavored fish such as salmon and tuna can even handle a light red wine, such as a pinot noir. The Tramin Pinot Grigio with a 4.4 out of 5 star rating seems like a good match. It costs about 11 dollars per bottle.

productMatches.title: Tramin Pinot Grigio
productMatches.description: Bright yellow in color with coppery reflections and clear fruit aromas of pear, citrus, honeysuckle, tropical fruits and light spices. Firm, velvety and rich on the palate, with well-integrated acidity. A very round and satisfying wine. Recommended with fish antipasti, risotto with asparagus, omelets and pasta
